Patch summary:
Fix an unsafe failure path in the guest gfxstream EGL implementation found while
investigating CarX Highway Racing (a Unity 2022.3 il2cpp title) rendering solid
black despite starting, running, and continuously submitting new frames on an
x86-64 host.

Root cause chain, confirmed live via adb/logcat on a running instance:
- The host correctly negotiates its real max GLES dispatch version per
  session (`host/render_control.cpp`'s `calcMaxVersionFromDispatch()`); on the
  test host this run settled on ES 3.1, which the guest correctly receives via
  `ANDROID_EMU_gles_max_version_3_1` and reports through
  `ExtendedRCEncoderContext::getGLESMaxVersion()`. Unity 2022.3, which requests
  the highest context version available, asks for ES 3.2 anyway and is
  correctly rejected by `egl.cpp`'s `eglCreateContext` with
  `EGL_BAD_CONFIG: no ES 3.2 support` -- this part of the guest/host
  negotiation is working as designed, not a bug.
- Immediately afterward (same thread, same frame), a config-attribute query
  fails with `eglDisplay.cpp`'s "Bad attribute idx." (attribute not present
  in the set the host reported via `rcGetConfigs`), which `eglGetConfigAttrib`
  correctly turns into `EGL_BAD_ATTRIBUTE` for callers that check the return
  value. But the lower-level `eglDisplay::getAttribValue()` this call goes
  through returns `EGL_FALSE` on that path *without writing `*value`* --
  leaving the output parameter uninitialized. Any caller that reads `*value`
  before (or instead of) checking the boolean return -- a real-world pattern
  this file already defends against for `EGL_FRAMEBUFFER_TARGET_ANDROID`,
  `EGL_COVERAGE_SAMPLES_NV`, `EGL_COVERAGE_BUFFERS_NV`,
  `EGL_DEPTH_ENCODING_NV`, and `EGL_COLOR_COMPONENT_TYPE_EXT` via explicit
  special-casing a few lines above this function -- gets whatever garbage was
  left on the stack instead of a defined value. That is consistent with an
  app's post-rejection fallback silently configuring a broken surface/context
  and continuing to submit frames that never show real content, instead of
  failing loudly or falling back to a supported ES version (3.1 in this case).

What this patch does: makes `eglDisplay::getAttribValue()` write a
well-defined value (0) before returning `EGL_FALSE` for an unrecognized
attribute index, matching the "always leave the output parameter in a defined
state" contract every other special-cased attribute in this file already
follows. This cannot regress any caller that correctly checks the `EGLBoolean`
return (they were already required to ignore `*value` on failure); it only
removes an uninitialized-read hazard for callers that do not.

diff --git a/guest/egl/eglDisplay.cpp b/guest/egl/eglDisplay.cpp
index 4607b10d..30c04050 100644
--- a/guest/egl/eglDisplay.cpp
+++ b/guest/egl/eglDisplay.cpp
@@ -451,6 +451,14 @@ EGLBoolean eglDisplay::getAttribValue(EGLConfig config, EGLint attribIdx, EGLint
     if (attribIdx == ATTRIBUTE_NONE)
     {
         GFXSTREAM_ERROR("Bad attribute idx.");
+        // Some callers (e.g. eglCreateWindowSurface/eglCreatePbufferSurface's
+        // inline EGL_SURFACE_TYPE probe, and app fallback paths that run after
+        // a rejected context/config request) do not all check this function's
+        // EGLBoolean return before reading *value. Leaving it uninitialized
+        // lets whatever garbage was on the caller's stack pass for a real
+        // attribute value, which can silently corrupt surface/config decisions
+        // instead of failing loudly. Give it a well-defined, inert value.
+        *value = 0;
         return EGL_FALSE;
     }
     *value = *(m_configs + (intptr_t)(getIndexOfConfig(config))*m_numConfigAttribs + attribIdx);
